title: Debt
description: From 2000 to present\, the U.S. debt (owed by federal\, state and local governments) increased from $1T to $20T due to three main expenses: ‚Ä¢ trillions for annual federal budget deficits from 2002 to today (Every year since 2002\, the federal government spent more than its income. The 2019 deficit is expected to be $1T. The 2018 deficit was $0.8T\, which was due to $4.1T in spending and $3.3T in income.) ‚Ä¢ trillions for impacts of the Great Recession from 2007 to 2014 (The recession was mainly due to unwise banking regulations and worsened by oil prices of $80+ per barrel. Impacts included reduced tax revenue ‚Äî from reduced\, and lost\, incomes of workers ‚Äî and from increased government welfare benefits for the underemployed and unemployed.) ‚Ä¢ $2T for wars in Iraq and Afghanistan Of the $20T debt\, Americans hold most of it. The Chinese and Japanese each hold $1T. Future costs: ‚Ä¢ $120T+ in unfunded\, future liabilities of the federal government\, such as for future Social Security benefits owed to 70+ million baby boomers. ‚Ä¢ trillions more on healthcare as well as Medicare and Social Security benefits for baby boomers. ‚Ä¢ a few trillion on restoration of America‚Äôs infrastructure and impacts of climate change. Annual deficit: ‚Ä¢ Since 1976\, America‚Äôs private debt grew each year that we spent more on imports than we earned from exports. ‚Ä¢ Today's annual trade deficit is $0.5T. (It peaked at $0.8T in 2008\, when high oil prices contributed to devaluation of the dollar.) - Potential Solutions - All of the above solutions. Increase tax revenue by increasing (taxable) personal incomes through solutions described in the Wealth Gap section. Avoid repeating mistakes\, such as by improving banking regulations and investing more in renewable energy. Consume less imports and/or increase exports. Reduce government spending\, and increase tax rates. (These solutions are usually unpopular with the public.)

title: I am asked these three questions most often:
description: 1.) What do I do? I orchestrate change. Just as an orchestra conductor works with individual musicians\, sections\, and the whole orchestra to bring them all together to improve performance\, I work with people\, teams\, and organizations to help them break free from the self-limiting beliefs and ineffective behaviors that keep them from reaching their full potential and magnifying their professional and personal effectiveness. 2.) How do I do it? When you work with me you get three things: a guide\, a catalyst\, and a partner. First\, you get a deeply experienced guide who not only has successfully coached dozens of teams\, but who has 30+ years of corporate experience in many different industries. I've been where you are ‚Äì from the cubicle to the boardroom. Having a guide that understands the entire terrain of the journey is a tremendous advantage. Second\, you get a catalyst for the change you are seeking. In nature nothing changes without a catalyst. Transformational change is about working with individuals and teams\, educating\, guiding\, and influencing so that we can unlock their potential\, empowering them to be the change that they want and the organization needs. Third\, you get an open and honest partner who will walk this path beside you - one who listens to your unique concerns and who works with you to co-create a solution that is tailored for your particular situation. Having and experienced guide\, a persistent catalyst\, and a pragmatic partner provides you with a powerful advantage on this transformational journey. 3.) Why do I do it? We must escape the limited Industrial Age thinking and advance to Information Age thinking. We need everyone contributing at their best. Empowering people to realize their highest potential is critical for us all to thrive.

description: Bilal‚Äôs Trio consists of Bilal Irshed on oud\, Rasmus M√∏ldrup on double bass and Yohan Ramon on percussion. The trio plays both modern original and traditional music from the Middle East and gives an absorbing portrayal of contemporary music styles played within traditional oriental music. The goal of the trio is to generate interest in a more classic and quality-conscious dimension of Middle Eastern music. The trio‚Äôs repertoire consists of original compositions written by Bilal Irshed as well as re-arranged traditional pieces. When it comes to choosing this material the trio has been very critical and only chosen the best from some of the greatest composers in the history of Arabic and Turkish music. In 2011 Bilal released his first album with the Trio. The music on the album\, ‚ÄòCompositions‚Äô\, was written and arranged by Bilal over a number of years and the album was therefore the result of many influences from his travels and experiences. Bilal¬¥s Trio is a tribute to the sound of the oud\, whose warm and meditative sound serves to capture the history and the beauty of the Orient. However\, by combining this sound with a Cuban percussion and the double bass from the Scandinavian jazz tradition\, the oud has been placed in a more interesting and contemporary context.

He is also credited with having added a fifth string to the then four-stringed oud. According to legend\, Ziryab coloured the first four strings so that they would symbolise Aristotle‚Äôs four temperaments.Then he added a fifth that would represent the soul. It is from this fifthstring that the project draws its inspiration. The Fifth String was created by Bilal and the music consists of original compositions combined with new arrangements of traditional Middle Eastern tunes. The sound and atmosphere of chamber music was then added to these compositions\, serving to create a whole new musicalexperience and sound. In 2011 the ensemble recorded and released their first album entitled ‚ÄòThe Fifth String‚Äô. The recording took place in Copenhagen\, Nazareth andand Bethlehem\, which ensured that both the classical and the Middle Eastern parts were recorded by true specialist in their field. description: I am grateful to many people during my time of transition as they shaped my outlook on career and life. - Companions on ski lifts who are equally passionate about their jobs as they are on skiing. They included weather forecaster for the Airforce\, NYC fireman and stay-at-home dad. I know you will be successful because you love your jobs and I heard it in your voices. - Fitness instructors and coaches who pushed me outside boundaries of comfort. You love what you do and make me feel I can achieve anything because I survived your class. - Career counsellor and job recruiter who were as caring as they were professional. I am fortunate to have you look after my interests and even more fortunate to call you friends. - People I met in interviews who were genuine\, candid and fun. You gave me choices but also difficult career decisions\, for which I am grateful. - My previous team members who have all dispersed. Great memories and we have all moved on for the better. I am sure I will have the honor of working with some of you again. - ExCo peers who didn't call to say goodbye\, probably because they were feeling bad for me. I will reach out again if you don't do it first. - Colleagues who told my spouse (who works for same company)\, words of support and praise. I received your messages which were enlightening and comforting. - Dearest colleague and friend who would 'take a bullet for me'. Your testimonial\, wisdom and advice has made me a better person. - Three teenage children who I spent valuable time with\, until I was brutally told to go back to work because I wasn't a good stay-at-home mom. I guess I have your permission to return to work! - Partner in life who gives me courage\, has been both a leading and trailing spouse in the many cities we have lived in\, and shared our responsibilities at home so we can both be successful at work. I have been lucky in knowing the best. Sometimes it takes a little hardship to fully appreciate love and companionship in its many forms.
